Problem 2
We will a consider a variant of the random coefficients demand model where instead of choosing 1 good, individuals can buy or not buy each good separately. Goods are index by \(j =1, ..., J\). The utility of individual \(i\) from buying a set of goods \(\mathcal{J} \subseteq \{1...J\}\) is \[
\sum_{j \in \mathcal{J}} \delta_j + x_j \Sigma \nu_i + \epsilon_{ij}
\] where \(\delta_j \in \R\), \(x_j \in \R^k\), \(\Sigma \in \R^{k \times \ell}\), \(\nu_i \in \R^\ell\), and \(\epsilon_{ij} \in \R\). Assume that \(\epsilon_{ij}\) are independent and Type-I extreme value distributed. Consumers buy the bundle of goods that maximizes their utility. In other words, \(\mathcal{J}\) will be bought if \[
\delta_j + x_j \Sigma \nu_i + \epsilon_{ij} \geq 0 \forall j \in \mathcal{J}
\] and \[
\delta_j + x_j \Sigma \nu_i + \epsilon_{ij} &lt; 0 \forall j \not\in \mathcal{J}.
\]
Suppose \(\nu_i \in N(0,I_\ell)\). Write a function that computes the average probability that a bundle, \(\mathcal{J}\), will be bought given \(\delta\), \(x\), and \(\Sigma\).

